POLIOMYELITIS VACCINE: COMMENTS
*******************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
See Also
Poliomyelitis - India: alert 20000506223744
Poliomyelitis - India: background 20000520221735
Date: Mon, 22 May 2000 11:21:18 +0200
From: Ted Tulchinsky <ted.tulchinsky@moh.health.gov.il>

The report on cases of poliomyelitis, vaccine-associated paralytic
poliomyelitis (VAPP) and or acute flaccid paralysis in India cases by Steve
Berger raise questions as to the policy of relying on OPV alone in the push
to eradication.
During the 1970s, we faced polio epidemics in Gaza and the West Bank
despite good (75% ) coverage with OPV and the cases included some with 4
feedings of OPV. We succeeded in eliminating polio in these areas in the
late 1970s by a combined program of OPV and IPV, overcoming fresh
importation of the wild virus, interference with OPV by other enteroviruses
and VAPP (1-6). Only sporadic cases occurred in the early 1980s, and no
cases have been found since 1988. This was despite findings from time to
time of wild polio virus in the sewage of Gaza and other imported
diarrhoeal diseases such as a small cholera outbreak in 1994, resulting
from the return of many Palestinians to the area from all parts of the
Middle East where endemic poliovirus circulation was/is still prevalent.
The combination of OPV, either mixed or sequentially, can provide an
earlier control of the disease, because of the inherent advantages of each
vaccine. Israeli experience with IPV alone was a failure because it led to
a "'window of opportunity" for the virus among vulnerable persons over age
15 who had received OPV only in childhood, in the "Hadera outbreak" of 15
cases in 1988 (7).
The US adopted the combined/sequential approach for several years in the
late 1990s (8-10) until shifting to IPV only in 2000 (11). WHO has stuck
with OPV only, relying on National Immunization Days to make up for weak
routine coverage.This has been successful in many parts of the world (e.g.
South America).
The issue of final eradication may well necessitate a combined OPV/IPV to
eliminate VAPP as well as cases due to wild poliovirus, especially in areas
with less than ideal routine coverage with OPV, in such situations as
described in India (12).
References:
1. Melnick J.L. Combined use of live and killed vaccines to control
poliomyelitis in tropical areas. Development of Biological Standards.
1981;47:265-273.
2. Lasch, E.E. et al. Results of a program successfully combining live and
killed polio vaccines. Israel Journal of Medical sciences. 1983;19:1021-1023.
3. Tulchinsky TH, Abed A, Shaheen S, Toubassi N, Sever Y, Schoenbaum M,
Handscher R. A ten year experience in control of poliomyelitis through a
combination of live and killed vaccines in two developing areas. American
Journal of Public Health. 1989; 79:1648-1655.
4. Tulchinsky TH, Handsher R, Melnick JL, Abu Shabaan D, Neumann M,
Budnitz D, Abed Y. Immune status to various strains of wild poliovirus
among children in Gaza immunized with live attenuated oral vaccine alone
compared with a combination of live and inactivated vaccines. Journal of
Viral Diseases. 1993;1:1-9.
5. Tulchinsky TH, Abed Y, Handsher R, Toubassi N, Acker C, Melnick J.
Successful control of poliomyelitis by a combined OPV/IPV polio vaccine
program in the West Bank and Gaza, 1978-1993. Israel Journal of Medical
Sciences. 1994;30:489-494.
6. Goldblum N, Gerichter ChB, Tulchinsky TH, Melnick JL. Poliomyelitis
control in Israel, 1948-1993: changing strategies with the goal of
eradication in an endemic area. Bulletin of the World Health Organization.
1994;72:783-796.
7. Slater, P.E. et al. Poliomyelitis outbreak in Israel in 1988: a report
with two commentaries. Lancet. 1990;335:1192-1197.
8. Tulchinsky TH, Birkhead G. More on vaccine-associated paralytic
poliomyelitis. Letter to editor. New England Journal of Medicine.
1993;329:1968.
9. Tulchinsky TH, Birkhead G. Polio outbreaks: a tale of torment. Letter to
Editor. Lancet. 1994;344:1575.
10. Centers for Disease Control. Poliomyelitis Prevention in the United
States: Introduction of a Sequential Vaccination Schedule of Inactivated
Poliovirus Vaccine Followed by Oral Poliovirus Vaccine: Recommendations of
the Advisory Committee on Immunization Practices (ACIP). Morbidity and
Mortality Weekly Report,1997;46 RR-3: 1-25.
11. Centers for Disease Control. Poliomyelitis prevention in the United
States: updated Recommendations of the Advisory Committee on Immunization
practices (ACIP). Morbidity and Mortality Weekly Report. 2000;49 RR-5: 1-22.
12. WHO Collaborative Study Group on Oral and Inactivated Vaccines. Combined
immunization of infants with oral and inactivated poliovirus
vaccines:results of a randomized trial in The Gambia, Oman, and Thailand.
Journal of Infectious Diseases. 1997;175 (Suppl 1): S215-227.

