From: Martin Haditsch <martin.haditsch@travel-clinic.at>

As to the report from Stephen (Berger) I just wanted to point out (taking
into account that not all readers are "epidemiologists) that due to the
fact that most of the sick are children under 5 years old, polio must be
highly endemic [in India - many people are more aware of the plans of
eradication than of the big risk (and I must admit I realized the dramatic
situation only by reading the lines the second time) - so thanks to Stephen
- I hope all got the message!
--
Martin Haditsch, MD,PhD
e-mail: martin.haditsch@travel-clinic.at
[I cannot go on posting messages and data I do not understand. I cannot
tell from our own reports how many cases of paralytic poliomyelitis there
have been in vaccinated and in unvaccinated people in India or how many
virus isolates have been obtained from unvaccinated and vaccinated people,
or how much of the clinical paralysis observed has been due to wild-type
and vaccine virus and how much could be due to other causes, such as
Japanese encephalitis virus. VAPP, OPV, IPV -- I'm getting a headache!
Also, although it is fascinating, we do not intend to enter a discussion
regarding comparative usefulness of vaccination approaches. String cut.
Let's let W.H.O. and NGOs continue their good work on eradicating this
awful disease. - Mod.CHC
